  "answer": "**Manusmṛti Book 1 — Opening Frame**\n\nThe Manusmṛti opens (unknown-manusmrti-347b76, ch. 1) with a teacher-petition scene: great sages approach Manu, who sits in concentrated meditation, honor him duly, and ask him to declare 'the sacred laws for all the four varnas and for those born between them' (Mn_1.1–2). They acknowledge that Manu alone knows 'the true meaning of the purpose and reality of this entire ordinance of the Self-existent One' (Mn_1.3). Manu accepts ('Let it be heard', Mn_1.4) and immediately launches into a full cosmogony: primordial darkness, the Self-existent manifesting, the waters, the golden egg, Brahma emerging from it, then the unfolding of the elements, the mind, the ego, and finally the emanation of the four varnas from Brahma's mouth, arms, thighs, and feet (Mn_1.5–1.31). The chapter ends with Manu explaining that he himself composed this shastra and taught it to Bhrigu, who will now recite it.\n\nWhat the text commits itself to in these opening verses: dharma is cosmogonically grounded. The social order (varna hierarchy) is not customary or derived — it is hardwired into the structure of creation, inscribed in the body of the creator at the moment of cosmic origin. Manu's authority is ontological: he is Viraj, the first Male produced from Brahma, and the shastra he transmits was authored by the Self-existent One before the world began. The frame signals that this is not a human text open to negotiation; it is the revelation of a cosmic ordinance, and learning it purifies seven generations in both directions (Mn_1.105).\n\n**Yājñavalkya Smṛti Book 1 — Opening Frame**\n\nThe Yājñavalkya Smṛti opens (unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6, ch. 1) with a structurally parallel but philosophically distinct scene. The sages honor Yājñavalkya — identified as 'lord of yogis' (yogirāja) — and ask him the same question: declare the dharma of the varnas, life-stages, and others (Yj_1.1). But Yājñavalkya does not reply with a cosmogony. Instead, 'residing in Mithilā, that king of yogis, having meditated for a moment,' he says: 'In the land where the black antelope is found, there you should learn the dharmas' (Yj_1.2) — a territorial demarcation of the sphere of dharmic authority. He then immediately shifts to epistemology: he names fourteen sources of dharma-knowledge (Purāṇas, Nyāya, Mīmāṃsā, Dharmaśāstra, the Vedas and their Aṅgas, Yj_1.3), then lists eighteen authoritative Dharmaśāstra teachers — including himself ('Yājñavalkya') within the canon (Yj_1.4–5). He defines the mark of dharma as a gift 'given to a worthy recipient at the right place and time' (Yj_1.6), gives the roots of dharma as revelation, tradition, conduct of the virtuous, what is pleasing to one's own self, and desire born of right resolve (Yj_1.7), and then declares the supreme dharma: 'the vision of the Self through yoga' (Yj_1.8). An assembly of four Veda-knowers — or 'even one who is a supreme knower of the Self' — decides what dharma is (Yj_1.9).\n\nWhat the text commits itself to in these opening verses: dharma is epistemologically and experientially grounded, not cosmogonically. The text is immediately jurisprudential: it catalogs its sources, names its authorities, defines its subject, and ranks its claims. Yājñavalkya is a yogi-meditator in a named city; he pauses to reflect before speaking; he situates himself within a lineage of eighteen (not above it). The capping move — 'vision of the Self through yoga' as supreme dharma — is a Vedantic claim that places interior realization above textual or hierarchical authority. Unlike the Manusmṛti, which ends chapter 1 by maximizing Brahminical supremacy as the cosmic purpose of the entire text, the Yājñavalkya Smṛti ends its introductory section by opening a single knower of the Self as constituting a valid dharmic assembly.\n\n**Comparative Summary**\n\nBoth texts use the same petition-frame (sages → sage-authority, asking for dharma of the varnas and āśramas), but they commit to opposite foundations:\n- Manusmṛti: dharma is a cosmic ontology — the varna order is eternal and inscribed in the structure of creation; Manu's authority is pre-human and non-negotiable.\n- Yājñavalkya Smṛti: dharma is a jurisprudential-epistemic construction — its sources are enumerable, its authorities are a named lineage, and its supreme form is not hierarchical law but yogic self-knowledge. The text signals from verse 1 that it will be a more systematized, more self-aware, and more interiorized dharmaśāstra than its Manu counterpart.",
